@*
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    BnList — Phase 7.2 Task 1.4 (design §"BnList (the component)"): the
    virtualized list. GENERIC, and authored in .razor — @typeparam carries
    TItem through the Razor source generator into `public partial class
    BnList<TItem> : ComponentBase`, so "everything new is .razor" (7.1's
    recipe) holds for a generic component too; no .cs fallback was needed.

    THE SHAPE (design, verbatim): a BnScroll whose content is a LEADING
    SPACER (WindowStart × ItemHeight tall), the window's rows (each
    Height = ItemHeight, keyed by ITEM), and a TRAILING SPACER
    ((Count − WindowEnd) × ItemHeight). Spacers over absolute positioning:
    two extra views, no per-row position:absolute, and the synthetic content
    node's height is Count × ItemHeight BY CONSTRUCTION — the same
    arithmetic 6.2 pinned (lead + window·ItemHeight + trail always sums to
    Count × ItemHeight; BnListWindowTests pins the tiling identity).

    RECYCLING IS KEYED DIFFING — AND THE DIFF IS INSERT/REMOVE ONLY. The
    Task 1.1 empirical answer (KeyedWindowSlideTests): a sliding keyed
    window NEVER emits PermutationListEntry, because the surviving keys
    never cross — the row that leaves is one RemoveFrame (RemoveNode on the
    wire, the whole subtree with it), the row that enters is one
    PrependFrame at its sibling index, and the survivors are structurally
    untouched. That untouchedness is the point: a surviving row keeps its
    NODE, so its native view — an EditText's text, its focus — survives the
    slide. @key = THE ITEM, so row state travels with the item, not the
    position. (Consequence: items must be DISTINCT — Blazor throws on a
    duplicate key, by design. Two equal items in one window is a data bug,
    not a layout choice.)

    THE WINDOW IS PURE ARITHMETIC (BnListWindow.Compute — exhaustively
    unit-tested; this component only CONSUMES the tuple). Fixed ItemHeight
    is design decision 3: exact numbers, every frame predictable on both
    shells. The offset arrives RAW from the shell (rubber-band negatives,
    past-the-end after a shrink) and Compute clamps it; a scroll event on
    an unchanged window re-renders into an EMPTY diff — no patches, no
    churn (Blazor re-renders the EventCallback receiver unconditionally;
    the diff is the filter).

    A NOTE ON RE-ENTRY: a row that leaves the window is DESTROYED (its
    native view with it). If it scrolls back in, it is created FRESH —
    uncontrolled native state (text typed into an unbound input) does NOT
    survive leaving the window, only sliding within it. An app that wants
    text to survive eviction binds it (@bind-Value into app state), exactly
    as on the web. The demo deliberately leaves its inputs unbound: the
    state-travels proof is about VIEW IDENTITY.

    NOT here in 7.2 (ledgered in the design): variable row heights
    (estimate→measure→correct — its own named design problem), scrollTo /
    offset restore, horizontal lists.
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*@
@typeparam TItem

<BnScroll Width="@Width" Height="@HeightStr" OnScroll="HandleScroll">
    <BnView @key="LeadSpacerKey" Height="@LeadSpacerHeightStr" />
    @for (var i = _windowStart; i < _windowEnd; i++)
    {
        @* The 7.1 rule: copy the loop variable per iteration — the row
           fragment runs later, and fragments closing over `i` would all see
           _windowEnd. `item` is the @key: state travels with the ITEM. *@
        var item = Items[i];
        <BnView @key="item" Height="@ItemHeightStr">
            @RowTemplate?.Invoke(item)
        </BnView>
    }
    <BnView @key="TrailSpacerKey" Height="@TrailSpacerHeightStr" />
</BnScroll>

@code {
    // Spacer keys: static object identities, distinct from ANY item value by
    // construction (a string sentinel could collide with a TItem=string item).
    private static readonly object LeadSpacerKey = new();
    private static readonly object TrailSpacerKey = new();

    private float _offset;
    private int _windowStart;
    private int _windowEnd;

    /// <summary>The items. @key'd BY ITEM, so they must be distinct (Blazor
    /// throws on duplicate keys). Never null — defaults to empty.</summary>
    [Parameter, EditorRequired] public IReadOnlyList<TItem> Items { get; set; } = [];

    /// <summary>Fixed row height in dp/pt — REQUIRED and positive (design
    /// decision 3: exact window arithmetic; variable heights are ledgered
    /// with their own design problem). Every window row is emitted with
    /// exactly this height.</summary>
    [Parameter, EditorRequired] public float ItemHeight { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Viewport height in dp/pt — REQUIRED and positive. One number,
    /// two consumers: forwarded to the BnScroll viewport (stringified
    /// invariantly) AND fed to the window arithmetic. A flex-sized viewport
    /// (Grow/Basis) is deliberately NOT supported in 7.2: the window math
    /// needs the number .NET-side, and a viewport whose height .NET does not
    /// know cannot be windowed exactly.</summary>
    [Parameter, EditorRequired] public float Height { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Rows rendered BEYOND the visible span on each side, clamped
    /// at the list ends. Overscan absorbs the dispatch latency of a fling —
    /// the window only moves every ItemHeight dp of travel.</summary>
    [Parameter] public int Overscan { get; set; } = 4;

    /// <summary>Viewport width, forwarded to <see cref="BnScroll"/> (same
    /// string grammar). Null = unset (the un-styled invariant).</summary>
    [Parameter] public string? Width { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The row's CONTENT. BnList owns the row wrapper (a BnView of
    /// exactly <see cref="ItemHeight"/>, keyed by the item); this fragment
    /// fills it.</summary>
    [Parameter, EditorRequired] public RenderFragment<TItem>? RowTemplate { get; set; }

    private string HeightStr => ((float?)Height).ToStyleValue()!;
    private string ItemHeightStr => ((float?)ItemHeight).ToStyleValue()!;
    private string LeadSpacerHeightStr
        => ((float?)(_windowStart * ItemHeight)).ToStyleValue()!;
    private string TrailSpacerHeightStr
        => ((float?)((Items.Count - _windowEnd) * ItemHeight)).ToStyleValue()!;

    protected override void OnParametersSet()
        // Re-clamp against the CURRENT items: the 6.2 shrink case — content
        // shrinking under a scrolled viewport — resolves to the bottom window
        // instead of indexing past the end.
        => RecomputeWindow();

    private void HandleScroll(BnScrollEventArgs e)
    {
        _offset = e.OffsetY; // raw; Compute clamps (rubber-band, shrink)
        RecomputeWindow();
        // No StateHasChanged: Blazor re-renders the EventCallback receiver
        // after the handler. An unchanged window diffs to an empty frame.
    }

    private void RecomputeWindow()
        => (_windowStart, _windowEnd) =
            BnListWindow.Compute(_offset, Height, ItemHeight, Items.Count, Overscan);
}
